				<p><p>The R and T in "Rx" and "Tx" stand for "Receiver" and "Transmitter".</p>

<p>So the Transmitter from one device should be connected to the receiver of the other device. Thus:</p>

<ol>
<li>Arduino Uno Rx -> HC-06 Tx</li>
<li>Arduino Uno Tx -> HC-06 Rx</li>
</ol>

<p>EDIT: </p>

<p>Thanks to the pictures that I can now see, what are the values of the resistors on the Arduino Tx pin? 2.2k I think, but I cannot see very well. </p>

<p>In idle mode, both Tx and Rx should be high (5V). Can you verify this with a multimeter? <a href="http://www.exp-tech.de/service/datasheet/HC-Serial-Bluetooth-Products.pdf" rel="nofollow">This</a> pdf  (p.8) states that the Rx should be pulled high. I assume that is what you did with the resistors, but I am confused to why you have two resistors. Could you explain this please? Usually a simple 10k resistor to Vcc should be sufficient. Adding a resistor between the Arduino Tx and the cable will cause reflections because of the impedance change and affect the signal quality.</p>
</p><br>
